      "writtenOn": "2021-02-06T02:57:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I changed the check to \"errors.Is(rerr, ErrTerminate)\" so it will not affect the current behavior of timeout. Here was what I found for the current behavior of handling timeout: \n\n2021/01/20 19:28:32 Got global error: context deadline exceeded: global timeout reached (59m45s)\n2021/01/20 19:28:32 Test runner failed: context deadline exceeded: global timeout reached (59m45s)\n2021/01/20 19:28:32 Trying to run 57 remaining test(s)\n2021/01/20 19:28:32 Connecting to chromeos6-row17-rack10-host3:22\n2021/01/20 19:28:32 Failed reconnecting to target: context deadline exceeded: global timeout reached (59m45s)\n2021/01/20 19:28:32 Ran 144 local test(s) in 59m43.607s\n2021/01/20 19:28:32 Failed to run tests: context deadline exceeded: global timeout reached (59m45s)\n\nCurrently, runTestsWithRetry will continue run tests after timeout, but it will get a false in beforeRetry because it cannot connect to the DUT with a bad context for local test. I am not sure about its behavior for remote test because beforeRetry for remote test always returns true. Therefore, I would change the behavior of handling timeout if I use the condition \"ctx.Err() !\u003d nil\". I agree that changing behavior of the handling timeout is not within scope of this crbug. Therefore, I changed the condition to \"errors.Is(rerr, ErrTerminate)\". ErrTerminate is introduced in this CL and it is only used in the case of reaching maximum number of failures at this moment. Therefore, I think it is without scope of this CL.\n\nPlease let me know your opinion. Thanks.",
